messages.content: time to build (but make it good for people and the planet)
:zuck:
Ok I’ve been thinking about this lately
Has social media had a net positive or negative social impact?
imo net negative collectively, but net positive for me personally

I think it was net positive collectively before everyone had a smart phone in 2012-13. Then after the 2016 election it trended downwards and became extremely negative through substantial phone usage / glued to “news” culture.
Its really not that simple
pros and cons are the only way to discuss SM
has globalization had a net positive or net negative social impact?
it seems for me that social media has just been a vehicle for increasing globalization after all
personally believe globalization has been net negative
I'm kinda split, it has definitely accelerated innovation, which feels like a good thing, but also are people happier today than they were before idk, the typewriter?
globalization is net negative I think as well. But depends how social impact is looked at - are we talking about avg or net happiness, people helped,  etc...?
if we measure quality of life instead of happiness however, that one has improved a lot
the question would be what do we consider to be a good metric then

yes agreed. I also think there isn't one good metric. For example, There are existential threats that exist today as a function of globalization/industrialization. They do not necessarily presently harm people's happiness/quality of life, but they pose a looming threat.

imo happiness should not be a metric. I do think technology is about improving lives and it can have an effect on happiness, but at the end of the day your happiness is determined by you, not external factors like technology.

I'd push back a bit. I think happiness is heavily influenced by technology. I think people can learn to play an active role in their own happiness, or a passive one. Tech can facilitate or obfuscate that. There is a ridiculous uprise in youth depression/anxiety. Some of this I am sure is function of increased normalization and better tracking, but the uptick is undoubtly there and I think primarily fueled by tech.

Human consciousness >>> any technology “advancement”.

Lack of happiness is influenced by technology. I don’t think happiness is increased by today’s technology, at least not in its current forms.

I agree; the incentives built into current tech for the most popular platforms are to extract as much attention for ad dollars as possible. This may lead to a consumerist definition of "happiness" if you go out on a limb and say it helps people get goods/services they want, but when looking at overall life satisfaction, it is unlikely that the way that *current* most popular consumer tech is built is to increase wellness.
I'd actually say happiness is determined by your expectations, and expectations increase massively with innovation
I would say social media and tech together has brought people who were far away right next to them(the purpose it was set up for) but has pushed the person next to them far away.
so i feel it was a positive impact when it started globalizing but then turned negative
Agree. Would also add desire to that. I think expectation/desire also increases massively with globalization.
question: are tiny houses worth it?
I love living in really "cozy" settings. Tiny house movement is kinda odd to me, but I like the idea of living well-below your means.

larping poverty is weird to me, and i think a lot of the tiny house + general degrowth stuff has aspects of that. That being said, there is something very nice about having a smaller space that you actually care for and are happy to maintain daily
big houses are very overrated imo, id love to have a tiny house on more land over a bigger house on less.
i feel like people switch to tiny houses for environmental reasons too
yeah true, but then the question is why not live in a apartment/condo where your marginal impact is less?
i guess its just a question of availability though
People like it as well for the novelty of it as well. Also I imagine many choose over apt/condo because they like being disconnected from cities/industrialization
Also could be a question of taste. Tiny houses are a way to escape the bustle of the city and challenge the norms of urbanization
yeah im all for that. and tiny houses as ADUs seem like a very beneficial bandaid solution to housing woes in downzoned regions

Globalization has drastically reduced absolute poverty, child malnutrition, hunger, diseases like malaria and increased global access to health, sanitation, education and information 

I know this comes at a cost for eg Americans in the auto industry but speaking as someone born and raised in Brazil who directly experienced the positive consequences of globalization for the underprivileged, there’s a pretty extreme lack of perspective in the claim “globalization has been net negative” as someone said here

Of course you can complain that globalization has negative consequences for some workers in established industries due to e.g. increased competition, but keep in mind that just by working pretty much any job in the Bay Area, you belong to the global 1%. Globalization has been life changing for the bottom ~70% of the world population and it’s really out of touch to not even acknowledge that
@GabrielT this ignores the fact that trade agreements often increase poverty look at NAFTA
Do you think tech could surpass consciousness?

Absolutely not. But, I think people will continue to build technology and in decades (?) maybe centuries from now, you will have a divide between people that are protesting of forced participation in “smart” societies. The wealth distribution will be amongst those that base their life surrounding ioT / industries that rely heavily on deep tech / etc. I hope this isn’t in my lifetime , but when I have kids and their kids one day? Idk. 

To try and penetrate what humanity is, is to not understand the point of life. The reasoning will always go back to the fear of mortality, and mortality, in any concept,  is inevitable. The Giver is one of my favorite books, but even though it isn’t sci-fi / futuristic in technology, it gives the framework and outlook that any society that is monoculture / centralized resource heavy is for control and a fragmented version of what life is supposed to be.  

TLDR;; I believe technology should empower humans, but just as equally as we take strides, we (rarely) unlearn or never learn the concrete and traditional steps/skills that were needed before this technology existed. Like calculators. Why would I need a calculator in the 1600s. But today, i need them for the simple calculations on a daily basis, even if the average educated person has learned beginner algebra in school to solve relatively simple questions. You have to ask yourself what do you really need it for, and how much do we forget with the replacement of our brains doing the heavy lifting of the thinking?  🤷🏻‍♀️

>  Why would I need a calculator in the 1600s
triangular trade

> maybe centuries from now, you will have a divide between people that are protesting of forced participation in “smart” societies. 
the separation might be death

>  The wealth distribution will be amongst those that base their life surrounding ioT / industries that rely heavily on deep tech / etc. I hope this isn’t in my lifetime , but when I have kids and their kids one day? Idk.

Maybe people should die naturally. Not through prolonging life for the sake of prolonging. Too bad “natural” is subjective and will never be agreed upon. Also, people shouldn’t just be exiled / expedited death because they choose to not participate in superficial & artificial means.
Maybe in 1st world countries. Not across the world.

is it nano tech?
also, "choose to not participate" sounds a bit vague because I'm sure you didn't mean to include anyone who lives outside of normal means to be exiled/deathed
wdym by that? machines being smarter than humans? humans leaving their biological bodies behind?
is consciousness scientifically  reproducible in our lifetime (~50 years)

> machines smarter than humans
= or > (=>)

like every other part in our body, the human brain is built according to some blueprint. it‘s the most complex biological structure we know, so unfortunately (or maybe fortunately?) we don‘t know that blueprint yet. but assuming that consciousness is something coming from our brains and not something supernatural (given by god or whatever) it‘s just a matter of time until we figure out that blueprint and can then reproduce it artificially (like we can do it with lungs & hearts right now). will both of that happen in our lifetimes? i doubt it, but it all depends on how complex the brain really is (what we don‘t know yet as well). maybe our current ML models just need some additional tweaking until they can work like a real brain (which i doubt), or maybe our AIs are super far away and in no serious way comparable to our brain (which is far more likely imho)

TLDR: imo it will happen, but probably not in our lifetime
We agree on one thing at least
Time is the main factor
(Regarding morals and technology)
what do we disagree on? Or have you already stated your thoughts on this in a message above? sorry i‘m late to the discussion

I think a better question is even if it was possible to reproduce, how would we prove it anyway? Even GPT-3 (which I’m sure will look archaic ten years from now) has some applications that have made for convincing conversation.
^ this, Turing might be obsolete
but is GPT-3 conscious? Intelligence != consciousness, and I would argue that it isn't even intelligent, more like simulating it
...can we get back to talking about social impact? 😂

http://readmultiplex.com/2020/11/20/there-is-a-maximum-human-bandwidth-and-we-have-reached-it-every-computer-technology-moving-forward-is-impacted/
This article kind of captures and expresses my opinions on not believing that tech could "surpass consciousness". I don't really like debating on this topic because it just fetishizes the idea that we are incomplete as humans in this mortal life and need technology to live, when we actually don't.
